XXX

To Guarinus

You have frequently in conversation, and lately in a letter, commended your friend Nonius to me for his liberality to some particular persons; Ι shall join with you in his applause, if his bounty is not confined to those only. Ι would have the man of true

generosity assist his country, his kindred, his relations, and his friends3 his friends Ι mean in distress; not like those who chiefly bestow their presents where there is the greatest ability to make returns. Ido not look upon such, as parting with any thing of their own ; on the contrary, I consider their bounties as only so many disguised baits, thrown out with a design of catching the property of others. Much of the same character are those, who rob Peter to pay Paul, and seek a reputation for munificence by the practice of avarice. The first principle of genuine liberality is to be contented with what you have; and aster that, to cherish and embrace all the most indigent of your acquaintance, in one comprehensive circle of benevolence.
